==Styles and forms== {{anchor|The Baroque suite}}
===Dance suite=== {{see also|Suite (music)#Dance suite}}<!-- This section describes the same form; the two should be merged. --> [[File:Pannini, Giovanni Paolo - Musical Fête - 1747.png|thumb|upright=1.15|A large instrumental ensemble's performance in the lavish [[Teatro Argentina]], as depicted by [[Giovanni Paolo Panini|Panini]] (1747)]]''
A characteristic of the Baroque form was the [[Suite (music)#Dance suite|dance suite]]. Some [[Bach Suites|dance suites by Bach]] are called [[partita]]s, although this term is also used for other collections of pieces. While the pieces in a dance suite were inspired by actual dance music, dance suites were designed for listening, not for accompanying dancers. Composers used a variety of different dance movements in their dance suites. A dance suite often consists of the following [[movement (music)|movements]]: * [[French overture|Overture]]&nbsp;– The Baroque suite often began with a French overture ("Ouverture" in French), a slow movement which was followed by a succession of dances of different types, principally the following four: * [[Allemande]]&nbsp;– Often the first dance of an instrumental [[suite (music)|suite]], the allemande was a very popular dance that had its origins in the German [[Renaissance]] era. The allemande was played at a moderate [[tempo]] and could start on any beat of the bar.{{sfn|Kenyon|1997}}{{sfn|Estrella|2012}} * [[Courante]]&nbsp;– The second dance is the courante, a lively, French dance in [[triple meter]]. The Italian version is called the corrente.{{sfn|Kenyon|1997}}{{sfn|Estrella|2012}} * [[Sarabande]]&nbsp;– The sarabande, a Spanish dance, is the third of the four basic dances, and is one of the slowest of the baroque dances. It is also in triple meter and can start on any beat of the bar, although there is an emphasis on the second beat, creating the characteristic 'halting', or iambic rhythm of the sarabande.{{sfn|Kenyon|1997}}{{sfn|Estrella|2012}} * [[Gigue]]&nbsp;– The gigue is an upbeat and lively baroque dance in compound meter, typically the concluding movement of an instrumental suite, and the fourth of its basic dance types. The gigue can start on any beat of the bar and is easily recognized by its rhythmic feel. The gigue originated in the [[British Isles]]. Its counterpart in [[folk music]] is the [[jig]].{{sfn|Kenyon|1997}}{{sfn|Estrella|2012}}
These four dance types (allemande, courante, sarabande, and gigue) make up the majority of 17th-century suites; later suites interpolate one or more additional dances between the sarabande and gigue: * [[Gavotte]]&nbsp;– The gavotte can be identified by a variety of features; it is in {{music|time|4|4}} time and always starts on the third beat of the bar, although this may sound like the first beat in some cases, as the first and third beats are the strong beats in quadruple time. The gavotte is played at a moderate tempo, although in some cases it may be played faster.{{sfn|Kenyon|1997}} * [[Bourrée]]&nbsp;– The bourrée is similar to the gavotte as it is in {{music|time|2|2}} time, although it starts on the second half of the last beat of the bar, creating a different feel to the dance. The bourrée is commonly played at a moderate tempo, although for some composers, such as Handel, it can be taken at a much faster tempo.{{sfn|Kenyon|1997}}{{sfn|Mackay and Romanec|2007}} * [[Minuet]]&nbsp;– The minuet is perhaps the best-known of the baroque dances in triple meter. It can start on any beat of the bar. In some suites there may be a Minuet I and II, played in succession, with the Minuet I repeated.{{sfn|Kenyon|1997}} * [[Passepied]]&nbsp;– The passepied is a fast dance in binary form and triple meter that originated as a court dance in [[Brittany]].{{sfn|Little|2001a}} Examples can be found in later suites such as those of Bach and Handel.{{sfn|Kenyon|1997}} * [[Rigaudon]]&nbsp;– The rigaudon is a lively French dance in duple meter, similar to the bourrée, but rhythmically simpler. It originated as a family of closely related southern-French folk dances, traditionally associated with the provinces of Vavarais, [[Languedoc]], [[Dauphiné]], and [[Provence]].{{sfn|Kenyon|1997}}{{sfn|Little|2001b}}
Additionally, there are numerous other dance forms as well as other pieces that could be included in a suite, such as [[Polonaise]], [[Loure]], [[Scherzo]], [[Air]], etc.
===Other features=== * ''[[Prelude (music)|Prelude]]''&nbsp;– a suite might be started by a prelude, a slow piece written in an improvisatory style. Some Baroque preludes were not fully written out; instead, a sequence of chords were indicated, with the expectation that the instrumentalist would be able to improvise a melodic part using the indicated harmonic framework. The prelude was not based on a type of dance. * ''[[Entrée (ballet)|Entrée]]''&nbsp;– Sometimes an entrée is composed as part of a suite; but there it is purely instrumental music and no dance is performed. It is an introduction, a march-like piece played during the entrance of a dancing group, or played before a ballet. Usually in {{music|time|4|4}} time. It is related to the Italian 'intrada'. * ''[[Basso continuo]]''&nbsp;– a kind of continuous accompaniment notated with a new music notation system, [[figured bass]], usually for one or more sustaining bass instruments (e.g., [[cello]]) and one or more chord-playing instruments (e.g., keyboard instruments such as [[harpsichord]], [[pipe organ]] or [[lute]]) * The [[concerto]] (a solo piece with orchestral accompaniment) and [[concerto grosso]] * [[Monody]]&nbsp;– an outgrowth of song{{sfn|Dorak|2008}} * [[Homophony]]&nbsp;– music with one melodic voice and rhythmically similar (and subordinate) chordal accompaniment (this and monody are contrasted with the typical Renaissance [[texture (music)|texture]], [[polyphony]]){{sfn|Hyer|2013}} * Dramatic musical forms like opera, ''[[dramma per musica]]''{{sfn|Dorak|2008}}{{sfn|Shotwell|2002}} * Combined instrumental-vocal forms, such as the [[oratorio]] and [[cantata]],{{sfn|Shotwell|2002}} both of which used singers and orchestra * New instrumental techniques, like ''[[tremolo]]'' and ''[[pizzicato]]''{{sfn|Shotwell|2002}} * The [[da capo aria]] "enjoyed sureness".{{sfn|Dorak|2008}} * The ''[[ritornello]]'' aria&nbsp;– repeated short instrumental interruptions of vocal passages.{{sfn|Talbot|2001b}} * The [[concertato]] style&nbsp;– contrast in sound between groups of instruments.{{sfn|Carver|2013}} * Extensive [[Ornament (music)|ornamentation]],{{sfn|Roseman|1975}} which was typically improvised by singers and instrumentalists (e.g., [[trill (music)|trills]], [[mordent]]s, etc.)
