{{Infobox magazine | title = Demet | logo = | logo_size = 180px | image_file = Demet.jpg | image_size = 180px | image_alt = | image_caption = | editor = Celāl Sāhir | editor_title = | previous_editor = | staff_writer = | photographer = | category = Culture | frequency = once a week | format = | circulation = | publisher = | paid_circulation = | unpaid_circulation = | circulation_year = | total_circulation = | founder = | founded = 1908 | firstdate = | finaldate = 1908 | finalnumber = | company = | country = | based = | language = Ottoman Turkish | website = {{URL|http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:hbz:5:1-72710 Demet}} | issn = | oclc = }} The Ottoman women's [[magazine]] '''''Demet''''' ("floral bouquet") was founded in 1908 in [[Istanbul]], two weeks after the proclamation of the [[Second Constitutional Era]]. Altogether, seven issues exist, they were published once a week.<ref>Demet, 1st volume, 1324.</ref> [[Editor-in-chief]] and publisher was Celāl Sāhir (1883–1935). Even though the magazine was aimed at women, the editorial team of the first two issues was made up exclusively of men, such as [[Mehmet Akif Ersoy]] (1873–1936), Selim Sırrı (Tarcan) (1874–1957), and Enis Avni (1886-1958). Among the female writers were later [[Halide Edip Adıvar|Halide Salih Hanımlar]] (Halide Edip, 1884–1964), Nigar Bint-i Osman (1862–1918), and İsmet Hakkı Hanım. In addition to literary and scientific articles, what interested the female readers most were political publications.<ref>cf. Ruth Haerkötter: Maḥāsin. Ein Beispiel für die osmanische Frauenpresse der Zweiten konstitutionellen Periode, Wiesbaden 1992.</ref> Besides Kadınlar Dünyası (1913–1921), Maḥāsin (1908–1910), and Kadın (1908–1910), <ref>Demet</ref> is considered one of the first and most important women's magazines in the Second Constitutional Era.
