[[File:Godet-dress.png|right|thumb|175px|A skirt with godets on the seams.]] A '''godet''' ({{IPAc-en|ɡ|oʊ|ˈ|d|eɪ}} or {{IPAc-en|ɡ|oʊ|ˈ|d|ɛ|t}})<ref>{{OED|godet}}</ref> is an extra piece of fabric in the shape of a [[circular sector]] which is set into a garment, usually a [[dress]] or [[skirt]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Wolff | first = Colette | url = https://books.google.com/books?q=+inauthor:%22Colette+Wolff%22&source=gbs_metadata_r&cad=6 | coauthors = | title = The art of manipulating fabric | publisher = KP Craft | year = 1996 | location = | pages = | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-8019-8496-9}}</ref> The addition of a godet causes the article of [[clothing]] in question to flare, thus adding [[width]] and [[volume]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Silverman | first = Julia E. | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Power Machine Sewing | publisher = R.R. Smith | year = 1942 | location = | pages = | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref> Adding a godet to a piece of clothing also gives the wearer a wider range of motion.<ref name=style1942>{{cite web | last = Pepin | first = Harriet | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = 1942-Modern Pattern Design | work = | publisher = VintageSewing.info | year = 1997 | url = http://www.vintagesewing.info/1940s/42-mpd/mpd-08.html | doi = | accessdate = 2009-08-13}}</ref>
